<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="House move" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Change of address letter</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Philip Lee [FBB0040]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">This document is submitted in a personal capacity, not on behalf of any organisation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">The main point</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt"> of this submission is that the imposition of a tax on the use of a television set, in order to finance a particular broadcaster, is unjustifiable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">There are now multiple broadcasters in the UK and there is no need for the government to finance one broadca</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">ster in preference to the others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Details</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">The Television Licence is an anachronism. The imposition of </span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">a what</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt"> is effectively a tax on the use of a television set, in order to finance the BBC, cannot be justified.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">The tax is regressive because it is a flat</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt"> rate tax on all households, regardless of income. The </span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">regressiveness</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt"> of the tax is even greater because BBC programs are, on average, watched and listened to by the better off, paid for by all, including the worse off.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">The high level of prosecutions for n</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">on-payment of the licence fee clearly demonstrates the reluctance to pay the fee, in many cases for a service that is not wanted or used.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">The introduction of digital broadcasting throughout the UK provides a simple way of charging for BBC programs. By cha</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">nging to a subscription based service, the need for a tax could be removed and the financing of the BBC could be legitimised.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">Charging a subscription would decriminalise what should be a personal, commercial choice and would render obsolete the whole archa</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">ic process for prosecuting those who   do not want to pay for a BBC service that they do not want.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">There are now a large number of broadcasters in the UK and the BBC should compete with them on an equal basis. Government policy should be to promote variet</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">y and competition in broadcasting, not to protect the BBC.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">If the government needs to own broadcasting channels, these should be paid for out of general taxation and should be clearly designated as government channels, in a similar way to how the BBC World</span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt"> Service is operated.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">Eventually, when the BBC is operating as a viable commercial entity, the organisation should be privatised.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>